The maximum allowed border capacity for SE1->FI and FI->SE1 is 1900 MW after commissioning of third interconnector Messaure-Viitajärvi (Aurora Line project). The capacity will vary depending on network element limitations. The limitations are affected by border flows, ambient temperature and production mix. The topology of the series compensation on the three interconnectors between SE1 and FI will also affect the available capacity to the market. The actual allocated capacity will be decided by the flow-based domain for each particular market time unit.

Fingrid will update flow reliability margins.   Fingrid will update flow reliability margins (FRM) on border FI-SE1 in accordance with article 24(2) of the Nordic CCM. The change will concern both the directions on the border, thus FI-SE1 & SE1-FI. New FRM will be static 200 MW. Combined dynamic constraints and critical network elements with contingency which capacity is affected due to the change are listed in the document attached. Please also see NRCC website for additional information:  https://nordic-rcc.net/updatesnewsletters/ Attachment 'FG CNEC changes Aurora Line deployment.pdf' was added.

There is an outage for several of Trøndereenergis power plant in the NO3 areas due to grid erros caused by the storm Amy. For now we are not able to produce as planned at Brattset, Sokna, Håen and Sama that together has an installed production capacity of around 145MW. Update 15:25: Further more powerplant has been verfied effected by the power grid outages. Litjfossen and Ulset, this brings the combined capacity that is out at around 255 MW.

New information: Statnetts project to replace the old 300 kV line between Sogndal and Aurland 1 with a new 420 kV is delayed. New estimation is that the project will be done on Thursday 2th of October.   Statnetts project to replace the old 300 kV line between Sogndal and Aurland 1 with a new 420 kV has good progress. Our estimate is that the new line will be in operation with increased market capacity from September 26th. This will relieve a significant bottleneck in flowbased capacity calculation and increase the capacity southwards over Sognefjorden varying between 250 to 500 MW limited by a thermal constraint. The increased capacity will allow a higher production in the area around and north of Sognefjorden. Statnett expect that the power transfer still will be limited by our lines further south in NO5 and Gudbrandsdalen

The ramping limit for Baltic Cable (SE4-DE interconnector) will be adjusted for the transition from 60 min Market Time Unit (MTU) to 15 min MTU in the Energy Market SDAC. The ramping limitation will be changed from 600 MW between MTUs to 300 MW between MTUs. The change of ramping will be adjusted from trading day 30th of September 2025 for the delivery day 1st of October 2025.

The ramping limit for Nordbalt (SE4-LT interconnector) was adjusted for the transition from 60 min Market Time Unit (MTU) to 15 min MTU in the Energy Market SDAC and SIDC. The ramping limitation was changed from 600 MW between MTUs to 300 MW between MTUs. The change of ramping was adjusted from trading day 18th of March 2025 for the delivery day 19th of March 2025.

Because of an error in out internal systems , we have failed to inform the market that there will be an outage at Sunndal in hour 11, September 23rd. The outage will result in 422 MW less consumption in NO3.   We apologize for the late notice.

The maximum net transfer capacity (NTC) from Sweden (SE1) to Finland (FI) is dependent on the dimensioning fault in Finland. When dimensioning fault is 1000 MW or more, the NTC from SE1 to FI is maximum 1200 MW. When dimensioning fault is less than 1000 MW, the NTC from SE1 to FI is maximum 1500 MW. For more information: https://www.fingrid.fi/en/news/news/2022/impact-of-olkiluoto-3-on-transmission-capacity-given-to-electricity-market-between-finland-and-sweden-on-northern-interconnections

Holmen AB, the owner of Blisterliden Vind AB, is developing a new wind farm located in price area SE1 (Skellefteå Municipality). The new wind farm will consist of 14 turbines and is expected to reach a maximum output of approximately 98 MW by the end of November 2025. Production is scheduled to begin on September 22, with an initial output of around 10 MW by the end of September. Output will gradually increase as all turbines are commissioned. Updated information to clarify that capacities for the day-ahead market will be alloacted by the flow-based methodology starting from the 30th of Otctober 2024. Svenska kraftnät has procured additional countertrade resources in SE3 for the period December 2023 to December 31st 2025, in order to increase day-ahead capacity. The available countertrade volume will vary between 0 - 260 MW from October to April and between 0 – 150 MW (occasionally higher, up to 260 MW) from May to September. The capacity to and from the SE3 bidding area may be increased thanks to the available countertrade volume when deemed possible. The corresponding countertrade volume will not be offered in Day-ahead or intraday bidding. Procured resources: Rya KVV

Following the day-ahead flow-based go-live on EDD October 30th 2024, the ramping restriction on Fenno-skan (SE3-FI) and SwePol (SE4-PL) will be updated. For Fenno-skan a new ramping limit of 600 MWh/h will be implemented. The existing ramping limit for SwePol will be reduced from todays 600 MWh/h to 300 MWh/h.

Following the day-ahead flow-based go-live on EDD October 30th 2024, the ramping restriction on Fenno-skan (SE3-FI) and SwePol (SE4-PL) will be updated. For Fenno-skan a new ramping limit of 600 MWh/h will be implemented. The existing ramping limit for SwePol will be reduced from todays 600 MWh/h to 300 MWh/h.

Updated duration. Starting from the EDD 20th of March 2024, Svenska kraftnät will introduce a new virtual bidding zone SE3A for the intraday market alongside the current sum allocation SE3-SE3LS in the day ahead market coupling. The SE3-SE3LS border will regulate the total sum on SE3-NO1 and SE3-DK1 on day ahead market whereas the remaing ATC capacity will be allocated to SE3-SE3A with connection to SE3A-NO1 and SE3A-DK1.  SE3-SE3A will be used as the general name for both the sum-allocation and virtual bidding zone corridor. The capacity on SE3-SE3A will therefore also state the capacity on SE3-SE3LS (and vice versa).  During high east-west flows in SE3 the NTC for SE3>SE3A will vary depending on operational conditions and availability of reserves with respect to variations in load, production and grid status between 500-2000 MW. Also see the following UMM for more information: https://www.nucs.net/outage-domain/other-market-information/show?ummId=f39b2cb858ed4eb4ae5ed2fc33feadca%7C10X1001A1001A418

In some scenarios, unfavourable load flow conditions can cause internal grid limitations in NO1. These scenarios may occur with low consumption in NO1, high flow NO1>SE3 and with flow from NO5>NO1>NO2, in combination with high outdoor temperatures. The grid limitations will partially be handled with reduced capacities between NO1>SE3 and NO1>NO2. Reduction will be placed on the corridor with expected lowest socio-economic cost considering price differences and efficiency of the reduction. The capacities will be given according to the intervals below: NO1>SE3 800-2050 MW NO1>NO2 1700-2200 MW The sum of NO1>SE3 and NO1>NO2 will vary between 2500-4250 MW. Capacities in the lower intervals will be given with low consumption in NO1, high outdoor temperatures and low availability on remedial actions. Capacities in the mid to high interval will be given with lower outdoor temperatures and full availability of remedial actions. For outages in this period, any further reductions will be published in a separate message

This UMM will be replaced by this UMM from the 20th of March 2024: https://www.nucs.net/outage-domain/other-market-information/show?ummId=369a7985c5c847c9a888d8f9ec9b8635%7C10X1001A1001A418  Svenska kraftnät has introduced a new sum allocation SE3>SE3LS in the day ahead market coupling. The SE3>SE3LS border will regulate the total sum on SE3>NO1 and SE3>DK1. ATC in the intraday market coupling will be distributed equally to SE3>NO1 and SE3>DK1 borders according to the available capacity on SE3>SE3LS after the day-ahead turnout.  During high east-west flows in SE3 the NTC for SE3>SE3LS will vary depending on operational conditions and availability of reserves with respect to variations in load, production and grid status. The sum-capacity will be in the following intervals (but it can at times be lower): SE3>SE3LS: 500-2000 MW. See history for previous information.

As part of utilizing existing assets more efficiently, Statnett and Energinet are conducting a test on Skagerrak interconnector. In the period December 12th until March 1st, the market capacity on DK1-NO2 will increase from 1680 to 1730 MW sending end, and 1632 to 1680 MW receiving end. In case of exceptional high temperatures (exceeding 15°C), the capacity may decrease.

In the text below, the capacity intervals have been updated. End date has also been updated: In some scenarios, unfavorable load flow conditions can cause internal grid limitations in NO1. These scenarios occur with low consumption in NO1, high flow NO1>SE3 and with flow from NO5>NO1>NO2, in combination with high outdoor temperatures. The grid limitations will partially be handled with reduced capacities between NO1>SE3 and NO1>NO2. Reduction will be placed on the corridor with expected lowest socio-economic cost considering price differences and efficiency of the reduction. The capacities will be given according to the intervals below: NO1->SE3 800-2050 MW NO1->NO2 1700-2200 MW The sum of NO1->SE3 and NO1->NO2 will vary between 2500-4250MW. Capacities in the lower intervals will be given with low consumption in NO1, high outdoor temperatures and low availability on remedial actions. Capacities in the mid to high interval will be given with lower outdoor temperatures and full availability of remedial actions.

Updated event stop. In the period between 2020-2023, the ongoing upgrades of the transmission corridor, Western Corridor, will be completed. Until the re-construction is finalized, there may be need for capacity reductions on the HVDC corridors due to internal grid constraints, also in situations where there are no planned outages. This message describes the expected variations in these reductions. The affected HVDC-corridors will be NO2-DK1, NO2-NL and NO2-DE. In the period between 01.12.2020 until 12.05.2023 the need for total reductions may vary between 0-200 MW for both export and import. The reduction will vary based on the expected constraint and flow.  The reductions will be placed on the corridor with the lowest expected socio-economic cost. For more information, see link: https://www.statnett.no/for-aktorer-i-kraftbransjen/nyhetsarkiv/reductions-on-hvdc-cables-in-the-re-construction-period-of-the-western-corridor-2020-2023

According to previous market information (link below) Fingrid will further clarify that the net transfer capacity (NTC) from Sweden (SE1) to Finland (FI) is dependent on Olkiluoto 3 (OL3) nuclear power plant generation. At generation below 1000 MW, the maximum NTC from SE1 to FI is 1500 MW and generation between 1000 MW and 1300 MW the NTC will be changed respectively according to OL3 market information. At generation equal or above 1300 MW the NTC is 1200 MW.  https://www.nucs.net/outage-domain/other-market-information/show?ummId=7305233cc9dc41b894401297baadf86b%7C10X1001A1001A264  For more information: https://www.fingrid.fi/en/news/news/2022/impact-of-olkiluoto-3-on-transmission-capacity-given-to-electricity-market-between-finland-and-sweden-on-northern-interconnections/  EDIT 6.9.2022 NUCS link fixed & new link added for additional information

In some scenarios, unfavorable load flow conditions can cause internal grid limitations in NO1. These scenarios occur with low consumption in NO1, high flow NO1>SE3 and with flow from NO5>NO1>NO2, in combination with high summer outdoor temperatures. The grid limitations will partially be handled with reduced capacities between NO1>SE3 and NO1>NO2. Reduction will be placed on the corridor with expected lowest socio-economic cost considering price differences and efficiency of the reduction.  The capacities will be given according to the intervals below: NO1->SE3 300-1450 MW NO1->NO2 550-2200 MW The sum of NO1->SE3 and NO1->NO2 will vary between 1600-3650MW.  Capacities in the lower intervals will be given with low consumption in NO1, high summer outdoor temperatures and low availability on remedial actions. Capacities in the high interval will be given with lower outdoor temperatures and full availability of remedial actions.

Statnett refer to earlier information about general work to increase the efficiency in ramping restrictions on HVDC in steps. We also refer to the information about ramping restriction on NordLink from November 18th2020, and latest March 8th2021. The restriction has been 300MW/hour for the Day Ahead and Intraday market since the start of operation in December 2020. Statnett is still facing a situation where ramping from HVDC interconnectors connected to NO2 need to be restricted, but changes are now made to split the individual restrictions more evenly between the different Interconnectors.  Statnett and TenneT has agreed to increase the allowed hourly ramping for NordLink to 600MW/hour from November 10th2021 and will in addition implement a combined ramping restriction for NorNed and NordLink of 900MW/hour. At the same time the restriction for the Skagerrak interconnector will be changed from 600MW/hour to 450MW/hour.

An error has occurred in our spot report until Monday 18/10 in NO5, so that we have been awarded such a large volume that we are unable to deliver everything. Starting at. 6 to 22, there is a volume between 32 and 225 MW per. hour we are unable to deliver.

Statnett refer to earlier information about ramping restriction on NordLink November 18th 2020 and latest February 10th 2021. The restriction has been 300MW/hour since the start of operation in December 2020. The intention was to gain experience with how this new interconnector would influence system operations in Southern Norway before the allowed total ramping for HVDC interconnectors to NO2 was raised. Due to the flow patterns this winter and that NorNed have been out of operation for a longer period, we have had very few situations where the system has been tested as planned. We therefor need to extend the test period and the period with maximum 300MW/hour for NordLink. A new evaluation will be done in June.

Energinet will in general not offer upward regulation in Western Denmark (DK1) for countertrade towards TenneT Germany from 3 July 2020 to 31 August 2020. Energinet will still offer downward regulation in DK1 for countertrade and will reassess the situation after the Danish holiday period, i.e. around 1 August, and again at the end of August.   Under the Joint Declaration, Energinet is obliged to guarantee up to 1,100 MW of upward and downward regulation every hour, however Energinet cannot fulfill the obligation to secure upward regulation for this period.  Due to generation adequacy, i.e. ensuring sufficient generation to cover consumption, Energinet’s cannot ensure a level of upward regulation for countertrade towards TenneT Germany. If no remedial actions are implemented, Energinet expects many situations where there will not be sufficient upward regulation to mitigate an outage of the largest unit (N-1)  News on website: https://energinet.dk/El/Systemydelser/Nyheder-om-systemydelser/Modhandel-DK1-DE

Clarifation about the Midskog stations. Connection to a new 400 kV switchyard at Midskog. Infeed to the 220 kV grid at the power stations Stensjön, Olden, Juveln, Järpströmmen, Mörsil, Sällsjö and Kattstrupeforsen is limited to 0% of the aggreed maximum input of 714 MW. Depending on the conditions in the transmission system infeed up to in total 300 MW or 42% may be possible. It will be administrated by Svk Balance service according to a special routine. For the stations IK2 Midskog, Näverede, Stugun, Krångede and Svarthålsforsen the allowed input is limited to 64% of the aggreed maximum input of 775 MW. No special restriction at the new station CT11 Midskog.

Applies from 04.07.2020 at 00:00. TenneT and Energinet have successfully commissioned the new common 380kV/400kV-connection as replacement of the existing common 220kV-connection between DK1 (Kassö) and DE/LU (Handewitt – Replacement of Flensburg) within the frame of the so called East Coast Project.  The maximum NTC, in both directions, is from this date 2500 MW. TenneT’s Hourly Guaranteed NTC will change according to TenneT’s Commitment towards DG Competition from 2021. The actual hourly NTC is still subject to TenneT’s daily capacity calculation (any value between Guaranteed NTC and maximum NTC) and Energinet’s capacity calculation (any value up to the maximum NTC).  The effect on minimum capacities following TenneTs Commitment is published on TenneT website "http://tennet.eu/market-news" under “into East-Coast Project" (“Mittleachse”).

Statnett has made an investment decision to expand and renew Tveiten transformer station. The work includes the establishment of a new 300MVA 300 / 132kV transformer. It is planned to put the new transformer into operation in the autumn of 2024. In connection with the project implementation, some operations will require disconnection of 420kV Rød-Hasle. This could result in up to 1000 MW of reduced trading capacity NO1-SE3 with a total duration of up to one week.

The normal capacity NO4-NO3 will be 900-1200 MW. Capacity NO3-NO4 is normally between 0-400 MW. The normal total export capacity from NO4 will be 1500-1800 MW. Maximum import capacity to NO4 is normally 1050 MW. The maximum import capacity to NO3 will be 2600-3000 MW, in situations with high flow from NO1 and NO5. Total import capacity will usually be well below this level, as southbound flows to NO1 and NO5 may be expected.

Historically the maximum NTC for SE3>DK1 has been reduced due to grid limitations and reserve requirements in DK1. In assessment done by Energinet and Svenska kraftnät, these limitations are no longer applicable. With this UMM the maximum NTC for SE3>DK1 will be increased from 680 MW to its technical limit 715 MW. This is a first step in also achieving symmetrical maximum NTCs for the interconnector. A second step will be to apply symmetrical maximum NTC in both directions February 1st 2020.

The capacity on the crossborder connection SE1-FI will vary by the hour with the ambient temperature: <15 C= 1500 MW, 20 C = 1400 MW, 25 C= 1300 MW, 30 C= 1200 MW, >33 C = 1100 MW. Recent investigation at Swedish side of the lines has indicated more temperature dependency than has earlier been agreed between Svenska kraftnät and Fingrid in System Operation Agreement.

The southern branch of the SouthWest Link is planned to be available for commercial operation the 31th of October 2020. Due to problems with the cable joints, during trial test in 2019, all cable joints have to be replaced. Power transfer on the link can only take place when this work is done. The converter stations are planned to be taken in operation during winter 2019/2020 for voltage control. The maximum NTC is set to be 6200 MW for SE3>SE4 and 2800 MW for SE4>SE3 the 1st of January 2021.

Based upon a review of recent operational experience and grid modifications, Svenska kraftnät has determined that sufficient evidence exists to justify increasing the maximum NTC SE3>SE4 to 5400 MW.

The southern branch of the SouthWest Link is now planned to be available for commercial operation under trial conditions the 1st of July 2019. The maximum NTC between SE3 and SE4 is then estimated to increase by 1200 MW, which means a maximum NTC value of 6600 MW for SE3>SE4 and 3200 MW for SE4>SE3. During trial operation by Svenska kraftnät the capacity offered to the market may vary and when specific trials would affect available capacity this will be communicated in separate UMMs.

The normal capacity NO4-NO3 will be 900-1200 MW after the voltage upgrade on Nedre Røssåga-Klæbu.  The normal total export capacity from NO4 will be 1500-1800 MW. The maximum  import capacity to NO3 will be 2600-3000 MW, in situations with high flow from NO1 and NO5. Total import capacity will usually be well below this level, as southbound flows to NO1 and NO5 may be expected.

During winter load, the capacity from NO1->SE3 is normally between 2100-2145MW. Capacities NO2->NO1, NO5->NO1 and NO1A->NO1 are normally in the mid capacity range (see separate UMMs for these corridors). In situations with favorable load flow conditions and high reserve volume in NO1, capacity will be given in the high range.  Very cold weather giving net deficit higher than 6000 MW in NO1, will reduce the NO1A capacity below the normal range. Separate UMMs will be published if this occurs.

In the period from week 13 to week 40 in 2019 there will be extensive work in the 420 and 300 kV AC-grid in Southern Norway. This will affect the export and import capacities from/to NO2. The estimated export/import elspot capacity NO2-DK1 will in the period range between 582 and 1532 MW. The average elspot capacity NO2-DK1 in 2019 is expected to be 1300 MW. It is expected > 180 days with reduced capacity on the Skagerak link. Separate UMMs will be sent for the different outage events.
